      "archetype": "The Classic College Town Public University — Business, Agriculture, and Northern California Community",
      "oneSentenceSummary": "Chico State is a mid-sized public university in a genuine college town in the Sacramento Valley foothills, known for a strong College of Business, an award-winning agriculture program, and one of the most traditional, community-centered residential campus cultures in the CSU system.",
      "pipeline": "Approximately 15,500 undergraduates. Chico State is regionally recognized for its College of Business, agriculture and sustainable food systems programs, construction management, nursing, and teacher education. Regional Northern California employers in agriculture, construction, healthcare, and business recruit Chico State graduates heavily, alongside a growing Sacramento-adjacent professional services presence.",
      "hiddenPathway": "Chico State's College of Agriculture operates a working University Farm that gives students direct hands-on experience uncommon at comparably sized public universities, feeding students into California's enormous agricultural economy — the largest in the nation — with credentials that carry real weight among Central Valley agribusiness employers who value practical experience over pedigree.",
      "institutionalSecret": "Chico consistently ranks among the most beautiful and walkable public university towns in America, anchored by Bidwell Park — one of the largest municipal parks in the United States — running directly along the edge of campus. This creates an outdoor-recreation-integrated college experience that is difficult to replicate at urban or commuter-heavy CSU campuses.",
      "theRoom": "Chico is a genuine college town of about 100,000 people in the northern Sacramento Valley, roughly ninety minutes north of Sacramento. The compact, walkable downtown sits immediately adjacent to campus, and Bidwell Park's 3,600 acres provide direct access to hiking, swimming holes, and outdoor recreation within walking distance of dorms.",
      "lifestyle": "Community-centered, outdoors-oriented, and traditionally residential. Students engage with a historically strong Greek life presence, Division II athletics, downtown college-town culture, and an agricultural and outdoor-recreation identity distinct from more urban CSU campuses.",
